name: Cabin in Shea-Oak Log · ★4.76 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: The Studio is located in a very unique area. There are no close by neighbouring houses, you are moments off of the Sturt Highway which leads you to the heart of the Barossa in 10 minutes and to Adelaide in 50 minutes. The studio is situated at the southern end of our property which is close to the Sturt Highway, this is great for access but you can hear the road noise from the studio. You are surrounded by the Barossa Ranges, vineyards and broadacre crops. No one will bother you here!
host_about:
We are a family of 4 who live, work and play in the Barossa Valley. We live on a small vineyard and make our own wine. We love the big outdoors, camping, the Murray river and doing things as a family. 
We are true locals and know the Barossa inside and out.
We live on the property but are far enough away to not bother you at all and let you enjoy yourselves but close enough if you have any problems.

name: Guesthouse in Gawler River · ★4.73 · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: The Gawler River area is the closest flat farming area to Adelaide. Studded with gum trees the farm land is park like. The view to the East is of the blue Mt Lofty ranges sweeping round to the Barossa Valley.
host_about:
My family have farmed in Gawler River since 1847. My farm runs the oldest Poll Dorset sheep stud in the world, I also grow cereal crops. Having lived in Gawler River all my live I have a detailed knowledge of the area, its history and attractions.
I enjoy traveling, meeting people and have many friends around the world. Especially through a long involvement with Rotary Youth Exchange.

name: Cottage in Tanunda · ★4.89 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: We are on the edge of town in a residential street that feels more rural than township. Houses are on one side, and wineries and few homes on large allotments are on the other side. We are on the winery side!
host_about: We feel very lucky to live and work in the Barossa and hope you will enjoy exploring our region during your stay! We like the rural feel where we live, with vineyards just over our back fence, but we are minutes to the centre of the township. We enjoy our wine and food and the opportunity to relax, so we understand that our guests might just like to be left to do their own thing and enjoy some time out. We like to take short impromptu getaways. Hubby loves his footy and horse-racing hence Foxtel in the cottage for people who may not want to miss a game while away. I enjoy gardening as being surrounded by a natural setting is important to me. If you want recommendations of where to dine out and what to do, we are happy to point you in directions that we have experienced and recommend! Careers in hospitality brought us to the Barossa in 1997... we're still here!

The Ashmead family have enjoyed hosting many visitors over the years, and now offer Guest House accommodation to the public.

name: Cottage in Tanunda · ★4.91 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: What's not to love about being in the Barossa?! Beautiful scenery, amazing local food & wine, wonderfully friendly people. It's our little slice of paradise!
host_about:
We love food, wine and travel and really enjoy meeting guests from all over the world that stay on our property. We’re now ‘semi-retired’ after selling our winery business in 2021, but our guests can still enjoy a special bottle of wine made by Rolf! Full breakfast provisions highlighting local Barossa produce are also included.
We stay on top of communication with guests to ensure they have an enjoyable stay and also provide lots of useful local knowledge to help plan time in the region. Our goal is to make guests feel like they have a sense for what it's like to actually live in the Barossa. Stay with us for a unique visit to our beautiful region! 
Cheers, Cynthia & Rolf

name: Rental unit in Angaston · ★4.82 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 shared bath
neighborhood_overview:
Angaston is a quiet heritage town. A town walk is a must.
We are middle of the Barossa Valley close to the famous Barossa Farmers Market that is open every Saturday morning
Though we are set in a beautiful location with views up the valley overlooking vineyards and paddocks with ancient gums. We are only 5 minutes’ walk to a variety of the Barossa's top restaurants, pubs and cafes. As well as the butcher bakery, supermarket and pharmacy.
We are also right next to the walking/bike track that will take you into Angaston, Nuriootpa and now all the way to Gawler.
There are a couple of cellar doors and restaurants in Angaston within walking distance as well as many cellar door options throughout the valley.
Angaston is 8km from Tanunda and 7 km from Nuriootpa
As there is no public transport so a car is a must. Other options are booking a personalised vineyard tour, or utilising the local taxi service.
host_about:
Hi
We have lived in the Barossa for 25 years.
Jonathan runs a tour business Barossa taste sensations and Kate is a Physiotherapist.
we enjoy introducing our guests to the area and have a wealth of knowledge at our finger tips to help you have a fantastic stay

Gardening, animals, people, fine wine and food are a few of my passions.

name: Home in Angaston · ★5.0 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: Angaston, 'the Crown of the Barossa' is nestled in the Barossa Ranges. You will need to set aside a couple of days to walk and taste and experience all the Main Street and historic surrounds have to offer.  Welcome to country hospitality.
host_about:
Hi. Thank you reading some of my bio.
Sharing a love of travel and discovery awarded me the opportunity to call the township of Angaston my Barossa home, my life and my passion. 
I would love nothing more than to welcome you and share some of my favourite authentically Barossa things to do.
Whether it's exploring a winery or two. Purely for research purposes of course. Taking in the local markets, catching up with friends while sourcing some locally grown produce to accompany our world class wines.  Walking or jogging and taking in the serenity of the every changing seasonal countryside. And sometimes sharing that space with wild kangaroos is majestic. 
You may even find me in a quaint little winter sunny spot or curled up with a good read in front of the fire.
The yang side of my personality loves nothing more than changing up the pace a bit.  Pop on some bright lippy,  jump on a scoot'ntoot scooter while getting some Barossa wind on my face.
I enjoy attempting all manner of sports and outdoor activities. Learning some footy skills from the local teens or switching up to my summer pace, water skiing & wake boarding.
I love open air concerts, festivals, camping, gardening, building/construction/renovation. 
My latest interest is self sustainability and environmentally sustainable practices. 
My mantra carpe diem. 
I can't wait to greet you and share a little of my Barossa home.

name: Home in Kapunda · ★4.58 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Our neighbourhood is full of wonderful old stone buildings , is great for walks, and peaceful. The main street has everything you need.  Kapunda is close to everything .
host_about:
Hi there, 
I'm an artist and business owner living  in the Barossa Valley. I love characterful houses, homes and hospitality and I have  three accommodations available in South Australia.
I have a weakness for beautiful stone homes typical to South Australia, that have a European feel. I appreciate natural light, wooden floorboards, enhancing architectural features and preserving what works from the past whilst adding charm and modern comforts. I like my guests to feel they have a stylish home away from home. 
My renovations style is comfy French provincial with a touch of vintage and original artworks on the walls for a restful and inspiring stay.
I travel a lot myself so I appreciate what it is to arrive to a place that feels like you can kick your shoes off, pour a wine and relax.

name: Villa in Kapunda · ★4.76 · 2 bedrooms · 4 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
The barn is 18 minutes to Maggie Beers Farm shop and The Eatery ( a very delicious dining experience featuring local produce and shared plates style ) & 24 minutes to the Barossa Farmers Markets and all that ANGASTON and Vintners restaurant . Take in the sculpture park lookout with stunning views across the Barossa.

Explore the Kaiser Stuhl national park where you can see kangaroos if you keep your eyes peeled and tread softly.
Yalumba winery and many boutiques wines are great to visit in the area.

Tanunda is 30 minutes drive from the barn and has boutique shopping, more wineries, cafes restaurants and art galleries.

Local amenities, pubs, supermarket, park for the kids and landscaped duck pond, and country bakery.

The barn is a solid 1860s structure which has been converted with the help of an architect and a local builder to a very comfortable home and spacious living.

name: Cottage in Moculta · ★4.88 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Moculta is a quiet little hamlet of about 280 residents. It is served by two Lutheran churches, Gruenberg and Gnadenberg.  Both are historic and worth visiting.  A visit to the Barossa wouldn't be complete without a visit to the Barossa Valley Cheese Company to purchase some locally made cheese and crackers to go with your favourite wine.There are a number of wineries a short drive away, with Henschke Hill of Grace Winery and vineyard the closest. There is an information book with our selection of favourite  take away and restaurants for the information of guests.
host_about: John and Jan Shepherd have owned Lemke Cottage for 26 years.  Both have lead professional lives and have used the cottage as a weekend escape during this time. They have travelled extensively and stayed in B and B's rather than hotels and motels.  They decided to share their unique cottage with others and offer it as an Air BnB. They both enjoy overseas travel but also have travelled extensively throughout Australia.  John now runs a consultancy helping businesses grow, and Jan keeps busy with volunteering as a Justice of the Peace, Folk Dancing and Tai Chi.  They both enjoy music and regularly attend Adelaide Symphony Orchestra Concerts. They have 9 grandchildren and enjoy time with their family.

name: Home in Lyndoch · ★4.88 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Casa Rossa is located in Lyndoch, South Australia, Australia.

Lyndoch is a small but thriving town in the heart of the Barossa Valley, and is growing and improving constantly. From the property, it is about a twenty minute scenic walk into town, or a speedy five minute drive.

You should be able to stock up on most things in Lyndoch, especially if you are in need of a quick fix. There is an IGA and convenience store, hairdresser and beautician, pub, and a number of great restaurants and cafes. Make sure you get to the Lord Lyndoch bistro for dinner!

For bigger shops, head to Gawler, about a ten minute drive from the property, which has a shopping mall and main street strip with Coles, Foodland, Big W, Target etc, as well as a number of boutiques and specialty stores.

Local attractions and venues include cellar doors and art Galleries.
Hot air-ballooning
Helicopter Scenic flights
Lord Lyndoch Restaurant

name: Cottage in Seppeltsfield · ★5.0 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
We are uniquely positioned with the amazing neighbours we have. The Barossa is known for its food, wine, music, heritage and hospitality and along Seppeltsfield Road we offer this in spades!! Apart from our visually beautiful location with vineyards and rolling hills, we are right next door to Hentley Farm (you can walk there on our private path)
Surrounded by boutique cellars doors, three of the Barossa's best restaurants FINO, Appellation and Hentley Farm and it's also a short walk to the iconic winery Seppeltsfield Estate. Here they offer not only bespoke wine tours including tasting a 100 year old Tawny and other unique experiences, but also the Jam Factory studio with artisans in residence. These include a knifemaker, milliner, shoe maker and potter. You can even book to make your own knife (but plan and book well ahead!) You will also find Vasse Virgin who make luxe Olive oil body and food products & Octeine Coffee & Cafe.
Other wineries include Hentley Farm, Barossa V
host_about: Introducing people to all of the amazing things the Barossa has to offer is what we love to do.  We love the ever changing culture of the Barossa, the friendly community feel and sharing with guests local knowledge and the best kept secrets of this wonderful region.

host_about:
I am a full time business coach helping business owners create businesses that work for not because of them.  My clients are mainly in Australia, New Zealand and the US, and as long as time zones are compatible I can work with them from anywhere. Thanks to Skype I have conducted my client meetings from Jaipur (India), New York, Perth, Sydney, South Australia and San Diego.
Clearly - one of the  things I can't live without is travel.
And I can't live without my Kindle - which has lightened my travel load enormously. No more books to carry and leave as I pick up more.
I love great food and wine - I live in a wine region where the two go together.
I am a great guest. Quiet, fun, a reader and a walker.
My life motto is Stride Into Life.

name: Cottage in Pewsey Vale, Barrossa Valley  · ★4.87 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview:
The Pewsey Vale area was settled by English, Scottish and German settlers. Pewsey Vale is a part of the world-famous Barossa Valley food and wine region, famous for bold red wines, delicate Pewsey Vale Rieslings, and the finest boutique foods.

The Barossa and its surroundings offer a wide variety of activities from hot air ballooning to trekking, cycling, horse riding, fishing, kayaking, wine tasting and more.

Closest large stores:
Gawler (25min drive / 20km nth west) has a many large town facilities and services including;
•Supermarket open until 9pm mon-sat
•24 hr petrol station

The local town of Williamstown (10min drive / 10km west) has a small general store, cemist, hotel, and bakery etc.
We are close to the National Motor Museum in Birdwood 18km, the famous Collingrove hillclimb circuit, and some of the best driving roads in Australia, through the Adelaide Hills and Barossa Ranges.

A Barossa Valley information guide
host_about: We are a  retired couple who really enjoy living in the countryside, renovating historical buildings, gardening and hobby farming. Having hosted bed and breakfasts for many years, we enjoy meeting guests from all over the world and providing information on the Barossa area and beyond.
neighbourhood: Pewsey Vale, Barrossa Valley , South Australia, Australia

name: Villa in Tanunda · ★4.97 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: What's not to love about being in the Barossa?! Beautiful scenery, amazing local food & wine, wonderfully friendly people. It's our little slice of paradise!
host_about:
We love food, wine and travel and really enjoy meeting guests from all over the world that stay on our property. We’re now ‘semi-retired’ after selling our winery business in 2021, but our guests can still enjoy a special bottle of wine made by Rolf! Full breakfast provisions highlighting local Barossa produce are also included.
We stay on top of communication with guests to ensure they have an enjoyable stay and also provide lots of useful local knowledge to help plan time in the region. Our goal is to make guests feel like they have a sense for what it's like to actually live in the Barossa. Stay with us for a unique visit to our beautiful region! 
Cheers, Cynthia & Rolf

name: Home in Nuriootpa · ★4.54 · 5 bedrooms · 5 beds · 3 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Where are the best Barossa Cellar Doors? Well, many of them can be found along Seppeltsfield Road! These include Hentley Farm, 2015 James Halliday Wine Companion Cellar Door of the Year. Hentley Farm, Greenock Creek Wines,Tscharke’s Place, Izway, Rolf Binder, Heritage, Two Hands and Torbreck are just a few of the wineries along the nine kilometres of Seppeltsfield Road where premium Barossa wines, including many famous Barossa Shiraz wines (the variety the Barossa is most famous for) can be tasted. Whistler Wines is a fabulous spot to combine wine tasting with a platter in the gardens under a gum tree, then visit their rescued pet kangaroos! Many of the wines produced in the Marananga/Seppeltsfield/Greenock sub-region of the Barossa are world class.

We have small, single vineyard producers without cellar doors as well as iconic establishments including the historic Seppeltsfield Estate Winery founded in 1851 and Winner of the 2016 Qantas National Tourism Award for Best Tour
host_about:
There’s something very special about the Barossa. You can feel it in the landscape, in the people, the food and the wine. It’s a beautiful region, with villages, vineyards and farms dotting a patchwork vista. Barossans are famous for their generous hospitality, their love of a shared table and their passion for local food and wine. Festivals, celebrations, markets and music thrive here. Barossa is life’s great pleasures, in one unique place. 

We welcome you to Barossa. The place we love. The place we call home.

name: Home in Angaston · ★4.98 · 3 bedrooms · 5 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Pinecone Ridge is 2km from the main street of Angaston.

Angaston is arguably the prettiest of the towns in the Barossa. Set amongst rolling hills it offers a well-preserved heritage streetscape lined by large leafy trees. It also sits on the border of the Barossa & Eden Valleys making a perfect base from which to explore both wine regions. It is home to the Barossa Cheese Company, Yalumba, Vitners restaurant, and the not-to-be-missed Barossa Farmers Market amongst many other attractions.
host_about:
Hi! 

Pinecone Ridge is really a family project - we are all involved: Anne, Josh, Jeb, April & Isla.

We purchased the property in Nov 2017 as a family escape & renovation project. The property had previously been owned by a 92 year old gentleman with poor eyesight & needed lots of attention but we could see the potential & loved the views & location.

Running Pinecone Ridge is a family affair. April creates the welcome signs. Isla collects the pinecones. Jeb is Josh’s right hand man when it comes to maintenance. I get the privilege of escaping to the Barossa every week to clean & prep & often Josh is able to join me. In school holidays the kids help too. And we have all contributed to the eclectic styling of the home!

We have created Pinecone Ridge to be our family getaway - cosy, comfortable, fun, creative, peaceful, surrounded by nature - a place in which to clear the head & relax into a slower pace of life, yet also close to the action & deliciousness of the Barossa. We love sharing it with you and reading your reviews together. May you have a wonderful stay!

Anne

host_about:
Local Barossa family. Heather & husband Gordon together, offer you this accommodation in one of the historic buildings from the 1850s, in Lyndoch. Lovingly preserved and decorated, we hope our guests will relax and enjoy their stay. We’d be pleased to show you the original bakers oven which served the town for around 60 years. We live nearby and can respond to any requests, or can leave you to enjoy the serenity and luxury of our little piece of paradise!
We enjoy travel ourselves and experiencing AirBnB’s all over the world. Our guests come from all states of Australia, but also from nearly every continent, so it is a great pleasure to host  our guests from all walks of life. 
Enjoy all the Barossa Valley has to offer by basing yourself in Lyndoch with us. We particularly welcome our fellow South Australian residents, to enjoy some local tastes and experiences which are easily accessible, thoroughly delectable and exciting or relaxing - the choice is yours!

neighborhood_overview: Our Retreat is on the most scenic road in the Barossa with 15 wineries to discover, including the historic Seppeltsfield Winery. name: Barn in Penrice · ★4.88 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Just a short 3km drive away from Pondicherri, lies the historic village of Angaston. It boasts a diverse range of cafes, restaurants, two pubs, a supermarket, butcher, hardware, medical centre, post office, and speciality Barossa food businesses - offering something for everyone. The Barossa Farmer's Market is also only a stone's throw away and can be easily accessed by taking the dirt Saleyards Road. However, be wary of kangaroos that tend to frequent the vineyards.

The region is home to many high-quality wineries, restaurants, food establishments, and historic buildings that are just minutes away from Pondicherri. For those who prefer outdoor activities, there are numerous walking and cycling trails, as well as easy bushwalks - perfect for spotting kangaroos at Kaisersthul Conservation Park. For a bird's eye view of the region, try hot air ballooning or a helicopter ride. The options are endless, except for surfing!

name: Farm stay in Williamstown · ★5.0 · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: We are 5-15 minutes from regional towns and many cellar doors close by
host_about:
The saying is true: the grass is greener on the other side, especially as you cross the paddock and unlatch the galvanised farm gate at The Dairyman’s Cottage entrance. This is Barossa country chic at its finest with a clean style that is as comfortable as it is design savvy. 

This reinvented getaway dates back to the 1840s. Stretch out in the Chaff House, a workshop where grain was once crushed, or hole up in the Dairyman’s Cottage for a stay that shares a similarly unique past, operating more recently to milk cows. Both pads now make up a relaxed and unpretentious Barossa getaway and can be booked in conjunction with one another or as separate retreats. 

Guests can quite literally wake up and smell the bacon, thanks to a healthy spread of breakfast provisions and other fresh produce that come directly from paddock to plate. And although your Barossa itinerary is likely to be teeming with sojourns to cellar doors and eateries, it's hard to overlook the peace that lazing in the shade of the South Australian sun brings. Take in the rich pastures and surrounding panoramas of the grape-dotted Barossa Valley Ranges, by spending the evenings on the paved terrace with your feet up, sipping a glass of something smooth from neighbouring vineyards. 

It's instinctual to wander the working dairy facility, so why not introduce yourself to the residents on an afternoon farm walk and feed the heritage breed free-range pigs. And if there are any items you can no longer live without when back home, The Dairyman has an online shop to keep you stocked up on breakfast packs and more.

The award-winning Seppeltsfield Road Distillers are our near neighbours, and the renowned restaurant Appellation at The Louise is also within walking distance.

A drive along Seppeltsfield Road's iconic avenue of palms will wind you through the vineyards of the western Barossa with its well-known wine brands and intriguing small batch wine producers. Historic Seppeltsfield Estate is home to Seppeltsfield Winery, Vasse Virgin, Jam Factory Art & Design Studios and Fino restaurant. Just around the corner you'll discover Hentley Farm Cellar Door & Restaurant.

name: Farm stay in Barossa Valley · ★4.92 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: There are so many places to visit that are quite close to us.  Birdwood with the motor museum is 5 minutes drive away, Gumeracha with the big rocking horse and wildlife park is 10 minutes.  If you like fishing or kayaking, the Williamstown reservoir is less than 10 minutes down the road.  There is also the Lavender farm at Williamstown and the wineries at Lyndoch are about 20 minutes away.  If you enjoy walking, Mt Crawford forest is also less than 10 minutes away.  There are some beautiful cafes  and local pubs in all of the towns that are close by.  Tanunda wineries are approx 30 minutes away and also the Barossa valley Chocolate Company.  Mount Pleasant is approx 5 minutes away, so if you are going to a horse show we are close by if you want to stay.  Monarto zoo is also approx 40 minutes away.
host_about: I am a mortgage broker and my husband is a carpenter.  We enjoy renovating houses and are renting this one out for the first time as a bnb.  We own an alpaca farm in Cromer, where you can pat and walk the animals, we currently have approx 15 alpacas on the farm.  We have 3 grown children and 2 dogs.  We also enjoy travelling.

name: Guesthouse in Altona · ★4.86 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
We are just a 13 minute drive to Tanunda the cosmopolitan heart of the Barossa with the best restaurants, entertainment and cellar doors. Award winning winery Kellermeister is just a two minute drive from us. The winery is rated in the top 7% of Australian producers by Australia's acclaimed wine critic, James Halliday.

For those who are a bit more adventurous, the Altona CSR Landcare Reserve which is highly rated on Tripadvisor Australia is located just opposite our property. It has a 6km walking track and is a great place to observe the wildlife and vegetation. Or you could wander down on to the Barossa Trail which is a shared cycling and walking path that goes from the outskirts of Gawler through Lyndoch, Rowland Flat, Tanunda, Nuriootpa to Angaston.
host_about:
I made the tree change with my husband Kipi and our two children in 2017 having lived half my life in Melbourne's hip and busy inner suburbs and the prior half in Malaysia. Now I enjoy a slower paced life surrounded by beautiful nature and amazing people.  

I love cooking and entertaining friends and family around my table. Our little family also enjoys travelling, particularly back to Malaysia and Kenya to visit our big families.

We renovated and converted the run down pottery studio on our property to a charming little guesthouse for our friends and family to stay when they visit us. We are happy to share our slice of paradise with travellers and holidaymakers. Meeting new people is always a pleasure and I look forward to hosting you and making your stay a comfortable and memorable one.

name: Guesthouse in Mount Pleasant · ★4.96 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Mount Pleasant is a lovely country town that feels rural however is close to so many wonderful tourist destinations.The famous Mount Pleasant  Farmers Market on every Saturday morning 8am-12pm. Pick up wonderful fresh fruits and vegetables all locally grown.There are cakes, pastries and amazing coffee. The breakfasts are also wonderful with something for everyone. We have one hotel, The Robbers Dog a great little gin distillery , two bakeries, a lovely quaint book and gift shop in Mount Pleasant all within walking distance. Considered the gateway to the Barossa there are local wineries just ten minutes drive or a 30 minute drive and you will be in the heart of the Barossa, Tanunda and Angaston with countless attractions. Twenty five minutes in another direction and you can be sitting on the banks of the river Murray in the lovely township of Mannum home to the  paddle steamer The Murray Princess.We are also close to the Adelaide hills with many other wineries to enjoy.

name: Farm stay in Williamstown · ★4.91 · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: We are located in Southern Barossa - offering the best of both the Adelaide Hills and the world-famous Barossa Valley. So much to explore: the wineries, restaurants and cafés, bushwalking and birdwatching in nearby nature reserves, kayaking and fishing at the local water reservoirs, historic sites and cultural events, a swimming pool in Williamstown, farmers markets and so much more ... A pleasant walking trail is just at our northern border - a 20min walk to Williamstown's cafes and shops, in the shade of old gum trees, and you could meet the neighbour's 2 curious alpacas that keep the grass down along the walking path :-)  We have prepared a guidebook and will be happy to suggest some local attractions.
host_about: We are lifelong learners, loving and observing nature and gardens. We like to travel light and visit places with no crowds. We live in the Barossa Valley, South Australia, and have retired from our careers in web management (Nelly) and satellite communications (Stan). Nelly looks after the guest cabin and the gardens, Stan tends our vineyard and makes wine.

name: Home in Lyndoch · ★4.99 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Lyndoch is the 'Gateway' to the Barossa Valley/ The residence gives you local ambience and history whilst providing a touch of luxury (enjoy the wonderful king-sized four poster-bed!). You have the opportunity to explore this vibrant foor and wine region, with the main Barossa towns - Tanunda, Nuriootpa and Angaston, all an easy drive away. Wineries and boutique shopping abounds in the area around the BnB. The bicycle track from Angaston to Gawler and beyond, passes nearby. Our BnB is a great starting point for your cycling adventure.
host_about:
Local Barossa family. Heather & husband Gordon together, offer you this accommodation in one of the historic buildings from the 1850s, in Lyndoch. Lovingly preserved and decorated, we hope our guests will relax and enjoy their stay. We’d be pleased to show you the original bakers oven which served the town for around 60 years. We live nearby and can respond to any requests, or can leave you to enjoy the serenity and luxury of our little piece of paradise!
We enjoy travel ourselves and experiencing AirBnB’s all over the world. Our guests come from all states of Australia, but also from nearly every continent, so it is a great pleasure to host  our guests from all walks of life. 
Enjoy all the Barossa Valley has to offer by basing yourself in Lyndoch with us. We particularly welcome our fellow South Australian residents, to enjoy some local tastes and experiences which are easily accessible, thoroughly delectable and exciting or relaxing - the choice is yours!

name: Cottage in Tanunda · ★4.99 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Barossa Wineries…

The Barossa has a winemaking tradition stretching back to 1842 and, having escaped the ravages of the phylloxera virus that decimated many European and Australian vineyards in the nineteenth century, is home to some of the world’s oldest vines still in production. Today, the region is home to more than 150 wineries and 80-plus cellar doors. Whilst producers range from large-scale global operations to small-batch artisans they all retain a distinctly local character and visitors can be assured a warm welcome. The local tourist board provides a comprehensive guide to the region’s wine here. Here’s a few of our favourites (in no particular order):

Artisans of Barossa: a group of eight family-owned winemakers who share a tasting room on Murray Street, Tanunda – Hobbs of Barossa Ranges, John Duval Wines, Sons of Eden, Schwarz Wine Co, Purple Hands Wines, Spinifex, Lienert Vineyards and Chaffey Bros Wine Co.

name: Home in Seppeltsfield · ★5.0 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Located just off the iconic Seppeltsfield Road.. We are uniquely positioned with the amazing neighbours we have. The Barossa is known for its food, wine, music, heritage and hospitality and along Seppeltsfield Road we offer this in spades!! Apart from our visually beautiful location with vineyards and rolling hills, we are surrounded by boutique cellars doors, three of the Barossa's best restaurants and the iconic winery Seppeltsfield Estate. Here they offer not only bespoke wine tours including tasting a 100 year old Tawny and a heritage winery tour, but also house the acclaimed FINO restaurant, and the Jam Factory studio with artisans in residence. These include a knifemaker, milliner, shoe maker, jewellery makers and potters. You will also find Octeine Coffee Cafe, and Vasse Virgin who make luxe Olive oil body and food products.
Other wineries include Hentley Farm ( which is right next door to us), Izway Wines, Barossa Valley Estate, Two Hands, Greenock Creek Wines, Kalleske
host_about: Introducing people to all of the amazing things the Barossa has to offer is what we love to do.  We love the ever changing culture of the Barossa, the friendly community feel and sharing with guests local knowledge and the best kept secrets of this wonderful region.

name: Villa in Lyndoch · ★5.0 · 7 bedrooms · 11 beds · 3.5 baths
neighborhood_overview: Lyndoch is one of South Australia's oldest towns and is the gateway to the world famous Barossa Valley, just 56km north of Adelaide. It was the first Barossa town settled and the first vines were planted here. It still retains a quiet village feel, with the local hotel, supermarket, traditional butcher, bakery, library and post office a two minute walk away. Surrounded by vineyards and glorious red gums, Lyndoch is an ideal base for exploring all the Barossa has to offer.
host_about: I'm a self-employed musician and antique dealer. I'm outgoing, energetic and optimistic, with a keen sense of humour. name: Place to stay in Kapunda · ★4.91 · 7 bedrooms · 9 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
We think that you'll be surprised at just how much Kapunda has to offer. In addition to being only a short drive to the world renowned wine regions of the Barossa and Clare Valleys, the local area is worth exploring.

Book a tour of ANLABY STATION - a historic sheep station that has been lovingly restored including 20 acres of manicured gardens.
Explore the RETAIL outlets in the main street: homewares at KOCO HOME, plants and pots from PLANT POT & MORE, gifts and more at TINY NEST

ART & CULTURE plays a big role in Kapunda. Wander the streets to look at the award winning street murals and visit the regional gallery to pick up a piece or two.
If you are more serious about your creativity, enrol in a workshop to paint BLOOMS with Jacqueline Coates. You will need to book ahead - and hope that she is in town at the time and not in residence in Paris!

Of course - it's not far to other creative and culinary experiences:
Learn the in's and ou
host_about:
I have been lucky to have lived in some amazing places - from on a boat in Queensland, to a warehouse apartment in Collingwood, and now in the Barossa Valley where I own a 160 year old railway station.
As a traveller I love to immerse myself in the local culture of the places that I visit... but I know the importance of having a home to return to after a day of exploring (and maybe the odd wine tasting!).   The Station is a truly amazing but liveable space for groups of families and friends.   I am proud to share it with like-minded guests and I know that you will enjoy your stay in the Barossa.

name: Cottage in Seppeltsfield · ★4.75 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Seppeltsfield  is a charming and historic destination nestled in the picturesque Barossa Valley in South Australia. With its quaint heritage buildings, rolling vineyards, and a sense of timeless beauty, Seppeltsfield offers a captivating experience for visitors. Within a short walk is the renowned Seppeltsfield Winery, which boasts a rich heritage spanning over 170 years. Visitors can explore the historic cellars, indulge in exquisite wine tastings, dine at Fino Restaurant, enjoy a coffee at Octeine or immerse themselves with the local artisans including The Jam Factory, Vasse Virgin, Gardner Knives and more. After a long day enjoy the west facing verandah watching the sun setting over the palm trees and vines. Sit back and enjoy the quiet, serene surroundings while looking up at the stars and the Milky Way. Seppeltsfield is a delightful destination that captures the essence of the Barossa Valley's wine country charm.

name: Home in Greenock · ★5.0 · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Escape to Greenock, South Australia: 'The best-kept secret in the Barossa Valley'. Less than an hour from Adelaide’s CBD, the charming village of Greenock is the gateway to the Barossa Valley wine region.

Take a stroll down to El Estanco cafe for breakfast and coffee, lunch, or dinner at their ‘Friday Fiestas’. Enjoy a good pub meal at the 'Greenock', or a platter at one of the cellar doors which are within walking distance of your cottage stay. One of many local hangouts, Greenock Brewers’ have a selection of small-batch beers. If you need a pre-dinner snack, grab yourself a produce platter and while away the afternoon.

Explore the lovely towns of Sepplestfield and Maranaga just a few minutes' drive away or a little further on - the towns of Tanunda, Nuriootpa and also Angaston - here you will find the Barossa Farmers Market with its abundant selection of fresh fruit and vegetables, herbs, meats, speciality bread, Barossa’s famous smallgoods, fresh milk, stunni

name: Rental unit in Tanunda · ★4.14 · Studio · 1 bed · 1 bath
host_about:
The Wine Vine Hotel offers affordable accommodations in the heart of the Barossa wine region, less than 1.2 km from the Barossa Wine and Visitor Center.

All rooms at the The Wine Vine Hotel include air conditioning, electric blankets, and a private outdoor veranda.

You can enjoy a game of tennis on the court, and in the summer season between October and April you can enjoy a swim in the pool.

The The Wine Vine Hotel gives you easy access to over 100 wineries. Famous local attractions are Mengler Hill Scenic Look-out, Conservation Park Bush, and the Whispering Wall.

The Barossa Cheese Company, Lyndoch Lavender Farm, Concordia Fruit Wines, and Maggie Beer's Farm Shop are all a short drive from the motel.

Couples in particular like the location – they rated it 8.5 for a two-person trip.

name: Cottage in Angaston · ★4.98 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Angaston, South Australia, Australia . Angaston is the prettiest town in the Barossa with a rich history and beautiful gardens. it has a wonderful German butcher, bakery and gourmet cheese shop plus restaurants and cafes all within walking distance of The Rusty Olive.

At sunset, unwind with a glass of Barossa wine on the front verandah overlooking the old stone faced St Hugh's Anglician Church, opened in 1931.
host_about:
A short history of ownership... The Rusty Olive was built in 1900 and was bought in an unrestored state by Sue and Michael Falkenberg in 2008. Sue and Michael then spent some 8 years restoring it to the magnificent building you see today. The original stonework was preserved, and the interior completely rebuilt with a sympathetic mix of modern and existing features. 

The home was designed as a luxury retreat and has been operating as an Airbnb since 2018. In April 2022, Sue and Michael sold the property to the current owners, Adam and Marilyn Laws. They fell in love with the Rusty Olive after staying for two weeks early in 2022. Marilyn grew up in the Barossa Valley and most of her family still reside here. Now based in Sydney, they regularly return “home” to experience the great lifestyle and family experiences in the Barossa. 

We hope you enjoy your stay in The Rusty Olive.

name: Home in Kapunda · ★4.82 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Horse Side Tiny House sits in a small town near Barossa Valley in South Australia. Where you can explore restaurants, shops, and attractions for you to enjoy. So, make an endless list of things to do.

Our local recommendations:

- Pizza Bar and Takeaway serves a diverse selection of ingredients for dine-in and takeaway pizzas in town.
- One White Kite is a cafe that offers a delicious selection of pastries, light meals, coffee, and tea in Kapunda.
- Kapunda Mine Trail is a popular attraction that marks the first commercially copper metal mine in Australia.
- Kapunda Tourist Park is a camping and cabin accommodation set in a well-shaded park in Dutton Park, Kapunda.
- Whispering Wall is a popular attraction where "whispered words" can be heard 140 meters away from the other end of the dam.

If you want to know more, you can check out "Things to Do near Kapunda."
host_about: Tiny Away spearheads the tiny house eco-tourism in Australia. It started because of our desire to offer city dwellers the perfect place to escape from their hectic digital life in the city. Riding on the international trend in tiny houses, we have taken the tiny house movement one step further by partnering with land hosts and placing our beautifully designed and handcrafted tiny homes on wheels in spectacular rural settings. By integrating the concept of tiny houses with eco-tourism, we want to allow everyone a chance to experience the tiny house lifestyle - To Discover Nature and Stay in Comfort.

name: Villa in Tanunda · ★5.0 · 5 bedrooms · 5 beds · 5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Tanunda House is located in the attractive town of Tanunda which is the heart of the world renowned Barossa wine region. A walk around the neighbourhood will lead you down leafy streets past beautiful sandstone homes, historic cottages and a number of lovely old churches - a testament to the Lutheran settlement of the region. Only 50 metres from Tanunda House is Goat Square - an historic meeting place which is now a lovely green lawn surrounded on all sides by heritage 1840s stone cottages.
Restaurants, cafes and wine bars and a wonderfully eclectic selection of shops and galleries for browsing are a short 5 minute walk away from Tanunda House but if you get in your car you can be out driving past vineyards, wineries and charming villages within minutes.

name: Home in Tanunda · ★4.94 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Location:
Tanunda is situated in the heart of the Barossa Valley, one of Australia's most renowned wine regions. The town is surrounded by vineyards and rolling hills, creating a scenic and peaceful environment.

Community Atmosphere:
The community in Tanunda is known for its friendly and welcoming atmosphere. It has a mix of residents, including locals who have been in the area for generations and newcomers attracted by the beauty of the region.

Historical Charm:
Tanunda has a strong German heritage, and this is reflected in its architecture and cultural events. Historic buildings, charming cottages, and tree-lined streets contribute to the town's character.

Vineyards and Wineries:
The Barossa Valley is famous for its vineyards and wineries, and Tanunda is no exception. Residents and visitors alike can enjoy exploring the numerous cellar doors, tasting world-class wines, and attending events celebrating the local viticulture.

name: Cottage in Lyndoch · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Surrounded by vines dripping with grapes and rolling hills, the charming small town of Lyndoch is Mrs Magpie's home. Stroll to the local pub, The Lord Lyndoch boutique restaurant, The Ministry of Beer (Brewery Cellar Door), cafe and bakery. A country market in the town's institute is held on the second Saturday of each month featuring homemade goods and quirky treasures. Weave your way to Tanunda (only 10-15 minute drive away) past gorgeous vineyards and welcoming cellar doors.
Enjoy the peace and tranquillity of Lyndoch with everything the Barossa boasts at your fingertips.
host_about:
I love to laugh, eat potato chips, do yoga and write romance/mystery novels...not all at once of course! Though wouldn't that be hilarious! 

I am fastidiously clean but not OCD...potato chips are messy you know!!
And I value honesty and integrity above all else. 
Amy x

name: Home in Kapunda · ★5.0 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Horse Side Farm Stay sits in a small town near Barossa Valley in South Australia. Where you can explore restaurants, shops, and attractions for you to enjoy. So, make an endless list of things to do.

Our local recommendations:

- Pizza Bar and Takeaway serves a diverse selection of ingredients for dine-in and takeaway pizzas in town.
- One White Kite is a cafe that offers a delicious selection of pastries, light meals, coffee, and tea in Kapunda.
- Kapunda Mine Trail is a popular attraction that marks the first commercially copper metal mine in Australia.
- Kapunda Tourist Park is a camping and cabin accommodation set in a well-shaded park in Dutton Park, Kapunda.
- Whispering Wall is a popular attraction where "whispered words" can be heard 140 meters away from the other end of the dam.

If you want to know more, you can check out "Things to Do near Kapunda."

name: Home in Nuriootpa · ★5.0 · 4 bedrooms · 4 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: Located an hour’s drive from Adelaide, Nuriootpa is in the heart of the Barossa, famous for its world class wines and also home to some of the best culinary experiences in the region. It’s just a few minutes’ drive from the house to the town centre, where you can start your day with a coffee at the Fleur Social café before taking a stroll down the historic main street and exploring boutique shops. There’s a local Foodworks supermarket there too, or its less than 10 minutes’ drive to the Barossa Farmer’s Market in Angaston, open every Saturday morning. Indulge your sweet tooth at Linke's Bakery in Nuriootpa, or taste craft spirits infused with local botanicals at the Barossa Distilling Company’s rustic tasting room and bar. It’s also only a couple of minutes’ drive from the house to Maggie Beer’s Farm shop, where you can dine at The Eatery, purchase wines or take part in a cooking class. Coullthard Reserve is 5 minutes away by car, providing family friendly picnic areas, BBQ facilities,
host_about:
Hey I’m Mark!

After an extensive, colorful career performing on stage and in film/TV, I developed people skills which I love to utilize as a property host. People consider me to be a genuinely warm, polite and friendly person. 

I certainly love helping travelers enjoy their time here. My yardstick is treating
guests the way I like to be treated when I’m away from home. I work for MaisonNets, a boutique agency specializing in short-term rental management. The MaisonNets portfolio has over 125 properties, encompassing mid-range to luxury apartments and houses in Australia’s capital cities, as well as country homes and a villa in Bali. 

Our properties are all specifically selected for their amenities and prime location - the accommodation of choice for urban sophisticates, professionals, couples and families looking for a uniquely comfortable experience. 

With a focus on organic products, MaisonNets offers unparalleled personal service and attention to detail ensuring that you, our valued guest, have a wonderful stay with us.

name: Cabin in Tanunda · ★3.80 · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1 bath
host_about:
Hello ,

We are a family who have been running Airbnb’s since 2017. We love it and are very interested to expand it.

Aloe has just published her first book on the accommodation businesses. Aloe has published numerous other books on various topics and always loves to make our guests happy.

Aloe’s partner Nick is a saxophonist who has worked as a professional Musican for 25 years and now helps to manage our Airbnb’s as well.  Nick can be a bit talkative.

Sherry is an accountant and works on financial and cleaning projects.  She will be very helpful if you need anything.

name: Home in Kapunda · 4 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
host_about:
Hi there, 
I'm an artist and business owner living  in the Barossa Valley. I love characterful houses, homes and hospitality and I have  three accommodations available in South Australia.
I have a weakness for beautiful stone homes typical to South Australia, that have a European feel. I appreciate natural light, wooden floorboards, enhancing architectural features and preserving what works from the past whilst adding charm and modern comforts. I like my guests to feel they have a stylish home away from home. 
My renovations style is comfy French provincial with a touch of vintage and original artworks on the walls for a restful and inspiring stay.
I travel a lot myself so I appreciate what it is to arrive to a place that feels like you can kick your shoes off, pour a wine and relax.
